The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic by this year.
Possibly
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer almost all the services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that obliges the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
From the fact that Czech operators belong to the most dear ones in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
After all, it was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, who noted that the price of SMS is higher by us than in the rest of the Union.
Following the European Commission’s last steps in the field of roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created – for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really want to start the fight.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, here too we have three mobile networks and coverage high above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile phone operators like to be lazy about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>TU) , Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has often stressed in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (Otherwise, it might be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the market that led to a significant price drop, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were similar voices in Britain like us.
However, it has been proven that the place for such operators is there and that they can really succeed.
After all, we must not go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to actually operate, there are far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, that is, relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually come in low-cost, offer low-cost calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of more restricted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a target group not just recently.
This operator aims to say so specifically about men.
“Real men choose the Mobilking operator they like and can be trusted,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can assert a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever a operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have much expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone conversation with Mobile.cz.
Thus, it has indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not very favourable to this view.
Rather, they try to do everything because you do not create any competitor potential.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not hidden its interest in launching a virtual operator, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first it's better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe there will be better times.
Non-official information reveals that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this point, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subjects with a complex and serious project have addressed us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefónica O2 press section in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not noticed any vital and advantageous commercial project for both of us, on which it is possible to continue to build."
He added: “On the T-Mobil network, it will hardly be a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of our customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common fast mobile internet network.”
Competent authorities -with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The disturbances surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when operators hold on to something they know how to tie on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressuring <0xC4><0x8C>TU in the time of the creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by public access information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which you do not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been enhanced above all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would result in him and, above all, his high-demand services."
However, the total disinterest of the Czech regulatory bodies is surprising from the attitude of mobile operators.
It is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the lease agreement for the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Section, in response to our questionnaire.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not be surprising.
Instead, the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and, moreover, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate deal.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In the country where virtual operators commonly operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile services.”
But, of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really shocking in the whole situation is the almost thrilling harmony of these three actors resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it’s really just a coincidence, comes on its own.
Just as the same price of gasoline for all petrols is without a doubt the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so there is no corresponding greater responsibility for its market behavior.
The neccessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also lack the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
There is, of course, the analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, according to which telecommunications are the single market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessarial the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has – in the end, logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a little alarming that three mobile operators behave so strangely similarly.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps you out of the business.
This has already been found in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>TU's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved update of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that, from this, many experts were expected to improve the situation.
<0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives should know this more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one is looking
While we do not realize it, the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators remains, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile phone services, but are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
Thus, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
Price lists of these companies usually only reach the predetermined people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator appears as a classic corporate client, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
“If you present the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the terms of the contract, and it could result in the conclusion of cooperation with such a company,” Martina Kemrová answered the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 mentioned companies you can deal with thousands of customers.
No operator defends itself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they draw a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: “The law permits similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot have it in full as the usual customers of mobile operators.”
But that should be a little strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU.
In addition, another question opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to uncover similar activities and if it does not, you will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a considerable reduction in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries precisely in these cases the regulatory bodies intervened to defend not the mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and others came to him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies launch the whole case from one to the other like a boiling potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw the sponge.
If the backstage information is correct and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
