No shoes, no steering wheels, no clothes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments far from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look, or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go to the scene.
German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots by singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser-known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the schedule of the Flamenco Photography Month, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day increasing," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed “on the street” are “artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these greats you do not need to portray them in the scene,
Because their personality and character are internal.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco."
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a dial-up camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is capable of surprise every day."
Not the dance, the singing or the playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, capable of conquering the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, being exhibited these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Famous Flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, appear in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portraits are the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare yourself with people, characters that sometimes you don’t even know or that only give you a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to concretize my ideas.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people", is set up at the gallery El Fotómata, at number 20 via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next October 16.
