The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol levels to install in their car a system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of drunkness or if it is not blown into the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney General, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the Attorney General for Road Safety, the Directorate General of Traffic (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers reported more than once per drunk driving return to driving the car.
The alcohol lock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from moving if the driver does not blow, or when an alcohol concentration is detected higher than the permissible.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be at the expense of the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow to reduce up to 65% of violations committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: stopping these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, undoubtedly, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the PSOE in which it proposes to install this system in school buses, as it has already been done in France.
