Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a frightening, but in reality it doesn’t matter much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquia.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, most of you have been told that you spoke in sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the baby remembers nothing.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (being pissed), or sleep apnea, but it is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overeating situations.
In any case, it is still a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or the opposite (scream, scream, long speeches...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and eventually consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outpouring of the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g., if coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to exaggerate the baby before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that cause fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sonniloqui appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you'll interrupt him to sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and then he's resting.
Remember that if it seems very distressed and episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such a great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming to say, so you need to pay a lot of attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
Never tell the child that you could ask him questions during the night to know his secrets.
Not even for a joke.
Something like this is causing a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
