The Meeting - Blood Is Safe Again
Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shocked by the blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such tragedy and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the re-proposition of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delayed in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and la Société canadienne du sang for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood transfusions and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population in Quebec now had confidence in Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, says the one that has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its founding.
“And we didn’t know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau relationships, according to which when you have doubts and you could get a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, you take excision measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that undoubtedly this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
That period could have been reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is so significantly reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means you’ll need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV to be diagnosed with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health, says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that, in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“Necessities are increasing as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet intake.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average only constitutes 3% of Quebec’s population acceptable as donors.”
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period equal to one year.
“With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Poverty cases are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it’s hardly an hour to donate blood,” says desolated Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, cardiac valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public bank of ombilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank insertion of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, describing this practice of cord blood extraction as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that you can't have access," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
