The Psychology of Excess Licensing: Why Spend More Money?
At auction buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
New York University neuroscientists and economists have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in Science magazine men don’t want to stay back in a race like eBay auction, so they’re available to pay a higher price as well.
The research attempted to trace the nervous pattern of this "party" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging method (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body slipped under the brain cortex enters intense function when you lose the game.
This area of the brain, among other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-gratification" of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial follow-up survey.
In this investigation, three groups have tendered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the actual value of the product concerned and they made their bet.
To another group in addition to this, they promised that in the event of winning, they would receive another <0x24>15 prize.
The third group, on the other hand, would receive <0x24>15 before the auction, but the group members would lose the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winning".
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, so far, these explained the phenomena found in the auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating neurological imaging have helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to contact a doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients is 100,000, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and ittery, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g., water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal loss, saliva).
For travelers it is useful to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots are formed on the skin and white of the eyes, the stools become clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
A million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth consulting with a family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more tolerable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In the context of the bizarre investigation, an electroshock was performed on 12 Catholic believers and on as many atheists, while all of them watched a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part.
The test took place exactly this way: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermitage painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the exam hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would originate some kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it was not too different from the other and considered it to be a soothing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time frame received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious or other theme painting.
The Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "relaxed and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they realized 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but one must find the appropriate image.
“We need to look for an image toward which very positive feelings are nourished, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of the same caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a virgin Mary of quality bring better results?
