Mp3 readers under charge, put hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injury.
This is what the European Commission reports, citing the opinion of the European Union's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (CSRs) published today in a statement published in Brussels.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the high-volume device risk permanent loss of hearing capacity."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously harm their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - the EU's responsible continues - a clear risk emerges and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise caused by them.
"Scientists confirm that there is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now consider together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and mobile devices."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
These damages can be greatly limited by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment if they listen to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed current limits on the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods of time are at risk of permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
